Abalone Age Investigation

1 Abstract

This investigation is a regression supervised learning study of the relationship between the number of abalones rings against their physical measurements.

2 Introduction

Abalones have been classified as an endangered species due to overfishing which leads to regulations that prohibit fishing for abalones smaller than a certain threshold of measurements. We would like to investigate whether there is a significant linear correlation between the number of rings and size measurements of abalones.

3 Data set

Our dataset consist of 4177 observations and 8 attributes. It is retrieved from https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/abalone.

# Names found in `abalone.names` information file.
cols = c("sex", 
             "length",
             "diam",
             "height",
             "weight_whole",
             "weight_shucked",
             "weight_viscera",
             "weight_shell",
             "rings")

# Read the data from `abalone.data` file.
data_url = "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/abalone/abalone.data"
raw_data = readr::read_csv(data_url, cols)
raw_data

4 Analysis

4.1 Variable selection

First we looks at plots of rings against every other variables in the dataset and see if there are any which we can fit a line through.

# install.packages("GGally")
library(GGally)
my_fn <- function(data, mapping, ...){
p <- ggplot(data = abalones, mapping = mapping) + 
    geom_point() + 
    geom_smooth(method=loess, fill="red", color="red", se = FALSE) +
    geom_smooth(method=lm, fill="blue", color="blue", se = FALSE)
p
}
GGally::ggpairs(abalones, columns = 1:9, lower = list(continuous = my_fn)) + theme_bw(base_size = 10)

We only focus on bottom last row and right most column since they show plots of rings against every other variables and their correlations respectively. We plot two lines on every plots, one is a straight line and the other is a loose line. It seems that we might be able to fit a linear line through rings against length and diam as the loose line and straight line are relatively the same. If the two dots in height are not outliers and if we consider them valid then we wont be able to use height, since its loose plot doesnt show an approximately linear relationship. It might not be necessary to include other weight variables if we use weight_whole. Weight variables might need transformations.

4.2 Investigating Significance of Gender

Since we have a categorical variable, we will first check to see whether there is a significant difference between genders.

library(dplyr)
group_by(abalones, sex) %>%
  summarise(
    count = n(),
    mean = mean(rings),
    sd = sd(rings)
  )

          color = "sex", palette = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#FC4E07"),

# Compute the analysis of variance
res.aov <- aov(rings ~ sex, data = abalones)
# Summary of the analysis
summary(res.aov)

As the p-value is less than 0.05, we conclude that there are significant differences between genders.

4.3 Transforming weight

abalones_lweight = abalones %>% mutate(weight_whole = log(weight_whole),
                                weight_shucked = log(weight_shucked),
                               weight_viscera = log(weight_viscera),
                               weight_shell = log(weight_shell))
abalones_lweight = abalones_lweight %>%
  mutate(
    sex = case_when(
    sex == "A" ~ 0,
    sex == "I" ~ 1
  ))
my_fn <- function(data, mapping, ...){
p <- ggplot(data = abalones_lweight, mapping = mapping) + 
    geom_point() + 
    geom_smooth(method=loess, fill="red", color="red", se = FALSE) +
    geom_smooth(method=lm, fill="blue", color="blue", se = FALSE)
p
}
GGally::ggpairs(abalones_lweight, columns = 1:9, lower = list(continuous = my_fn)) + theme_bw(base_size = 10)
